 billions of dollars on clothing and equipment each year as they seek out nature, the American outdoor sector grew over the past 150 years from a small collection of outfitters to an industry contributing more than 2 percent of the nation’s economic output. Rachel S. Gross argues that this success was predicated not just on creating functional equipment but also on selling an authentic, anticommercial outdoor identity. In other words, shopping for the woods was also about being—or becoming—the right kind of person. Demonstrating that outdoor culture is commercial culture, Gross examines Americans’ journey toward outdoor expertise by tracing the development of the nascent outdoor goods industry, the influence of World War II on its growth, and the boom years of outdoor businesses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCamping equipment industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aOutdoor recreation industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aOutfitters (Outdoor recreation)zUnited StatesxHistory. 0aOutfitting industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSPORTS & RECREATION / Equipment & Supplies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074979340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300277302?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300277302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300277302/original  a978-3-11-074979-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles